04943nam a2200709Ia 9780674296848DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742968487 a10.4159/97806742968482doi  a(DE-B1597)685459  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aF1233b.J66 2024 7aHIS0250002bisacsh04a972/.07223/eng/202308141 aJonas, Raymond, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHabsburgs on the Rio Grande :bThe Rise and Fall of the Second Mexican Empire /cRaymond Jonas. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tPrologue: An Anti-Imperialist Empire -- t1 Rescuing the Latin Race -- t2 The Vicar of Cranborne -- t3 Puebla -- t4 Pacification and Resistance -- t5 The Savior -- t6 The Seduction -- t7 Imperial Pageantry -- t8 The Empire Looks for Friends -- t9 Volunteers and Refugees -- t10 Things Fall Apart -- t11 Charlotte Tries Diplomacy -- t12 Like Pinning Butterflies -- t13 Querétaro, Capital of Empire -- t14 Empire on Trial -- t15 Leaving Mexico -- tEpilogue: The Hill of the Bells -- tAbbreviations -- tArchival Sources -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe story of how nineteenth-century European rulers conspired with Mexican conservatives in an outlandish plan to contain the rising US colossus by establishing Old World empire on its doorstep.The outbreak of the US Civil War provided an unexpected opportunity for political conservatives across continents. On one side were European monarchs. Mere decades after its founding, the United States had become a threat to European hegemony; instability in the United States could be exploited to lay a rival low. Meanwhile, Mexican antidemocrats needed a powerful backer to fend off the republicanism of Benito Juárez. When these two groups found each other, the Second Mexican Empire was born.Raymond Jonas argues that the Second Mexican Empire, often dismissed as a historical sideshow, is critical to appreciating the globally destabilizing effect of growing US power in the nineteenth century. In 1862, at the behest of Mexican reactionaries and with the initial support of Spain and Britain, Napoleon III of France sent troops into Mexico and installed Austrian archduke Ferdinand Maximilian as an imperial ruler who could resist democracy in North America. But what was supposed to be an easy victory proved a disaster. The French army was routed at the Battle of Puebla, and for the next four years, republican guerrillas bled the would-be empire. When the US Civil War ended, African American troops were dispatched to Mexico to hasten the French withdrawal.Based on research in five languages and in archives across the globe, Habsburgs on the Rio Grande fundamentally revises narratives of global history. Far more than a footnote, the Second Mexican Empire was at the center of world-historic great-power struggles—a point of inflection in a contest for supremacy that set the terms of twentieth-century rivalry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh  aannexation.  ablack decree.  aborderlands.  acatholic church.  acharlotte.  aconfederacy.  aexile.  aindigenous.  amanifest destiny.  amariano escobedo.  amiguel miramon.  apeonage.  aporfirio diaz.  aqueretaro.  arace, geopolitics.  asettler colonialism.  aslavery.  atexas.  ayankee.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074971740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674296848?locatt=mode:legac